node.text:
Jinx Allen with guidebook gazing at Abduction of a Sabine Woman in “Staring at Statue” for the American Girl in Italy series, 1951. Photograph by Ruth Orkin.⁣
⁣
Carved from a single block of imperfect marble, the torturously twisting Abduction of a Sabine Woman, by the Flemish sculptor Giambologna, in Florence’s Loggia dei Lanzi, Piazza della Signoria, is one of the finest and most technically difficult sculptures in the world. Three intertwined bodies, two men and a woman, spiral upwards as the woman tries to escape the clutches of the younger man standing over the older one.⁣
⁣

node.text:
Kiki Smith, Constellation, 1996.⁣
⁣
Constellation is an installation based on the night sky. The circular field of leaves of handmade Nepalese, paper died in the go, is the backdrop for a collection of hot-sculpted class animals, cast glass stars, and cast bronze animal scat. The glass animals referred to 27 constellations. These include well-known star patterns—such as Ursa Major and Minor (Greater and Little Bear), Scorpius (the scorpion), Aries (the ram), and Cancer (the crab)—and lesser-known star patterns, such as Corvus (the crow), Lacenta (the lizard), and Delphinus (the dolphin).⁣
⁣
⁣
Source:⁣
https://www.flickr.com/photos/autisticreality/30266619050⁣

node.text:
Etruscan Red-Figure Amphora, C. 325-300 BC.  Now on display at Hermitage Museum, Russia.⁣
⁣
From Vulci (map) in Etruria. With dolphins, hippocampi, and sea dragons.  The Vulci was an ancient tribe as well as a city. They were one of the legendary twelve peoples of the Etruscan civilization, who formed into the Etruscan League, a confederacy of self-interest. This league splintered apart when opposed by the central government of the Roman Republic, and the Etruscans were soon assimilated and thus Vulci was abandoned.⁣
⁣
